  "prompt": "Can somebody explain how time is relative in layman's terms?",
  "response": "Sure! The idea of time being relative comes from Einstein's theory of relativity. Here\u2019s a simple way to think about it:\n\nImagine you are at a train station, and you see a train moving very fast. Now, picture two people: one standing still at the station and another person on the train.\n\n1. **Time for the Train Passenger**: The person on the train experiences time as they normally would. They have a watch that ticks away seconds, minutes, and hours just like yours.\n\n2. **Time for the Station Person**: The person standing at the station sees the train moving fast. According to the theory, they would observe that the watch of the person on the train appears to tick more slowly than their own watch. It\u2019s as if time is stretching for the person on the train.\n\nThis effect becomes more noticeable the closer you get to the speed of light. So, if the train could somehow travel at that speed, the time experienced by the person on the train would slow down significantly compared to someone who is stationary.\n\n**Key Points**:\n- **Relative Time**: Time is not the same for everyone; it depends on how fast you\u2019re moving.\n- **Speed Matters**: The faster you go, the more pronounced this effect becomes. \n- **Gravity's Role**: Time also moves differently in stronger gravitational fields; closer to a massive object (like a planet), time ticks more slowly compared to a place with weaker gravity.\n\nIn essence, time is not a fixed thing; it can change based on your speed and where you are in relation to gravity. This is why we say time is \"relative\"!",
